George's answer is probably correct, making an http request with an `access_token` should error.  The response body should have something like `{
error_id: 406,
error_name: "access_token_compromised",
error_message: "Access token sent over non-HTTPS request, it has been invalidated"
}` in it.

Saw this in global-login.js

        `// WARNING: this happens on EVERY SINGLE PAGE 
        // this the core global login function for every user, even the anonymous ones that have no login 
        // the reason this stays sane is because we set this "gauthed" cookie on the first
        // attempt to do global auth, and we don't ever try again FOR THE CURRENT BROWSER SESSION`

It seems to be enough to add the following to the end of script.js - `if (site) {
        var wanted = lochash.substr(lochash.indexOf('wanted=')).split('&')[0].split('=')[1];
        if (wanted) {
            apiEndpoint = wanted;
            RefreshData();
        }
    }` - that lets you add something like `&wanted=comments` to the URL.

